<span class="displaytext"><b>"[the] testimony from general petraeus and ambassador crocker confirms the progress being made by our troops in iraq. this is good news for americans and iraqis. ... america must continue its commitment to the strategy general petraeus is executing." - gov. (candidate full)</b> ((candidate last) for president, press release, 9/11/07) <p align="center"> <b>the (candidate last) vision: support the troops and the surge</b> </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate last) welcomes the petraeus report and news that u.s. forces are making progress in iraq:</u> </b> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) called the petraeus report "good news for americans and iraqis."</b> (candidate last): "today's testimony from general petraeus and ambassador crocker confirms the progress being made by our troops in iraq. this is good news for americans and iraqis. the importance of a successful conclusion to iraq must be weighed in light of the global threat of violent jihad and terror. america must continue its commitment to the strategy general petraeus is executing." ((candidate last) for president, press release, 9/11/07) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- gov. (candidate full):</b> "and i think the american people listened with interest to general petraeus and ambassador crocker and recognized that we have true american patriots and heroes here. and they expressed their views openly. ... [t]hey pointed out the good and the bad. the net in both of their testimony was that we are making progress?" (wls 890 am's "don wade &amp; roma," 9/12/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b>gov. (candidate last) believes that "walking away" from the conflict in iraq would "present grave risks" to the u.s.</b> (candidate last): "all americans want u.s. troops to come home as soon as possible. but walking away now or dividing iraq up into parts and walking away later would present grave risks to the united states and the world. iran could seize the shiite south, al qaeda could dominate the sunni west, and kurdish nationalism could destabilize the border with turkey. a regional conflict could ensue, perhaps even requiring the return of u.s. troops under far worse circumstances." (governor (candidate full), "rising to a new generation of global challenges," <em>foreign affairs</em>, july/august 2007) </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate last) rejects the negative and defeatist (PARTY NAME) attacks:</u> </b> </p><p><b>governor (candidate last) criticized sen. (candidate last)'s plan, calling it a "flee-in-the-face-of-success strategy."</b> "(candidate last)'s push for withdrawal drew a sharp rebuke from (PARTY NAME) rival (candidate full). 'i think (candidate full) has disqualified himself for presidential leadership,' (candidate last) said in a telephone interview with the associated press. 'if we take the kind of left turn represented by (candidate full) and his flee-in-the-face-of-success strategy, we'd be in a very different position as a nation.'" (mike glover, "us presidential candidate (candidate full) calls for immediate, gradual withdrawal from iraq," <em>the associated press</em>, 9/12/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) believes that sen. (candidate last) has "disqualified himself" for president by advocating "cut and run" policies in iraq.</b> "so in some respects i think this was a defining moment for (candidate full) and he's disqualified himself for his ability to be president by virtue of the cut and run approach he took, which would have had severe consequences." (wls 890 am's "don wade &amp; roma," 9/12/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) believes that sen. (candidate last)'s policies would create a safe haven in iraq for al qaeda.</b> (candidate last): "well, thank heavens (candidate full) was not president over the last year, because had (candidate full) been president over the last year, osama bin laden would have been declaring victory in iraq. we would have had al qaeda as a dominant player in iraq. they would have had a safe haven, particularly in the sunni portion of the country. ... and i think the comments he's made over the last month... i think they've really disqualified him in the minds of virtually everybody who's serious about this country. this is a man who by virtue of politics and perhaps panic has suggested a course in iraq that would have led to al qaeda having a new safe haven." (fox news' "your world with neil cavuto," 9/12/07) </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate last) has pushed for a surge of support for our troops:</u> </b> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last): "i think it's time for american citizens and politicians to make a surge of support."</b> "'at a time when american families and individuals are making a surge of sacrifice to support this troop surge, i think it's time for american citizens and politicians to make a surge of support,' (candidate last) said wednesday in pelham, n.h., a comment he repeated throughout the day." (glen johnson, "(candidate last) donates $25,000 amid plea for patriotic 'surge'," <em>the associated press</em>, 8/2/07) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- gov. (candidate last) continues to encourage americans to show their support for our troops in any way they can.</b> "a father's concern about u.s. support for the military surge in iraq has prompted (PARTY NAME) (candidate full) to both make a $25,000 donation to a variety of military support agencies and urge americans to engage in a similar display of patriotism. the money will be divided between uso care packages, the fisher house, a soldiers wish list, packages from home, operation thank you, operation shoebox and america supports you. links to each site have been placed on (candidate last)'s presidential campaign web site, www.(candidate full).com." (glen johnson, "(candidate last) donates $25,000 amid plea for patriotic 'surge'," <em>the associated press</em>, 8/2/07) </p></blockquote> <p align="center"> <b>sen. (candidate full): cut and run</b> </p><p><b> <u>s